00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:17.552
is symmetric.

00:03:20.150 --> 00:03:22.820
One of the major important
physical applications

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:24.350
of the Riemann
curvature tensor is

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:27.020
that it allows us to
describe the way in which two

00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:30.740
neighboring geodesics-- if
I have two geodesics that

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:34.310
are separated by
a four vector c,

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:38.000
and I look at how that
separation evolves as they move

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.810
forward along their geodesic
paths, this differential

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:43.460
equation describes
how it behaves.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:45.290
And the key thing
is that what we see

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:49.670
is that the rate of separation
is proportional to the Riemann

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:50.570
curvature.

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:52.430
It ends up playing
the role-- when

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:56.360
we think about-- what this tells
us is this ends up, remember,

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.610
geodesics describe free fall.

00:03:58.610 --> 00:04:02.270
And so what this is telling me
is a way in which two nearby

00:04:02.270 --> 00:04:05.960
but somewhat separated--
separated by a distance c--

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:08.450
nearby but slightly
separated geodesics-- both

00:04:08.450 --> 00:04:11.630
are in free fall, but their
free fall trajectories

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:13.490
are diverging from
one other and perhaps

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:14.900
being focused
towards one another

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:18.110
depending upon how R
is actually behaving,

00:04:18.110 --> 00:04:19.810
this is the behavior of tides.

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:21.860
Free fall is
gravity, and this is

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:24.050
saying that the free
fall trajectory's

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:27.920
change of separation is
governed by the Riemann tensor,

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.220
and that's telling me about the
action of gravitational tides.

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.390
The last thing that we did
in Tuesday's-- excuse me--

00:04:35.390 --> 00:04:38.690
in Thursday's lecture was I went
through and I developed this

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:41.180
proof of what is known
as the Bianchi identity,

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:45.260
which is an identity on the--

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:47.270
it's an identity on the
covariant derivative

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:48.630
of the Riemann tensor.

00:04:48.630 --> 00:04:50.120
And so notice what's
going on here.

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:53.360
I'm leaving indices 3 and
4 on the Riemann tensor--

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.160
oh shoot.

